{"id":"1103.4246","submitter":"Maxim Barkov","authors":"Maxim V. Barkov, Alexei S. Pozanenko","title":"Model of extended emission of short Gamma-ray Bursts","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1111/j.1365-2966.2011.19398.x","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Until now the existence of extended emission is an intriguing property of\nshort bursts. It is not clear what is the nature of the extended emission. It\nmight be a rising x-ray afterglow, or it could be a manifestation of the\nprolonged activity of a central engine. We consider short duration gamma-ray\nbursts, emphasizing the common properties of short bursts and short burst with\nextended emission. Assuming that the extended emission with broad dynamic range\nis a common property of short bursts, we propose a two jet model which can\ndescribe both short main episode of hard spectra emission, specific for short\nbursts, and softer spectra extended emission by different off axis position of\nobserver. The toy model involves a short duration jet powered by heating due to\n$\\nu\\tilde{\\nu}$ annihilation and long-lived Blandford-Znajek jet with\nsignificantly narrow opening angle. Our proposed model is a plausible mechanism\nfor short duration burst energization, and can explain both short burst with\nand without extended emission within a single class of progenitor.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Mar 2011 11:28:34 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 6 Jun 2011 13:33:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-27"}
